query = "Select d.*, c.*, m.*, p.*, t.* from sales.transactions t join sales.date d on d.date = t.order_date join sales.customers c on  c.customer_code = t.customer_code Join sales.markets m on m.markets_code = t.market_code join sales.products p on p.product_code = t.product_code"

df = pd.read_sql(query, conn)

In [85]:
num_plots = len(object_columns)
plots_per_row = 2 
num_rows = -(-num_plots // plots_per_row)  # Calculate number of rows

fig, axes = plt.subplots(num_rows, plots_per_row, figsize=(15, 5 * num_rows))

# Flatten axes array in case it's 2D
axes = axes.flatten()

for i, col in enumerate(object_columns):
    df[col].value_counts().head(10).plot(kind='bar', ax=axes[i])
    axes[i].set_title(f'Frequency of {col}')
    axes[i].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=15)


plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

As we can see in the frequency of currency plot we have duplicates 'INR' and 'INR \r' same to 'USD' and 'USD \r'

Why is this happening?¶

** 1.MySQL Query (SELECT DISTINCT currency FROM sales.transactions)¶
  • MySQL ignores trailing spaces and special characters like \r (Carriage Return) by default.
  • This is why you see only **two unique values: 'INR' and 'USD'.
** 2.Pandas Output (cust_df['currency'].unique())¶
  • When data is fetched into Pandas from MySQL, it may retain hidden characters (\r).
  • This results in duplicate values like INR\r and USD\r.
array(['INR', 'USD', 'INR\r', 'USD\r'], dtype=object)

#setting Million in the xticks
formatter = FuncFormatter(lambda y, pos: f'{y*1e-6:.0f}M' if y >= 1e6 else f'{y:.0f}')
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(formatter)

#Text value in the bar
for barh in bars:
    plt.text(barh.get_width() - (barh.get_width()/2),  # Position text
             barh.get_y() + barh.get_height()/2,  # Center vertically
             f"{barh.get_width()/1e6:.1f}M", #Million
             va='center', ha='left', fontsize=10, color='black')

plt.show()

  1. Few sales amount are below 0, we might need to remove those.
  2. Remove duplicates of USD and INR
